          "body": "Many readers stop at verse 9, missing the chapter's hinge. Verses 10-12 are written in imperfect/future verbs and describe a Servant who, after His death and burial (v.9), *sees His offspring*, *prolongs His days*, *sees* the result of His anguish, and is *satisfied*. A dead Servant cannot see offspring or prolong days. The chapter requires bodily resurrection as the logical predicate of its closing stanza. Paul reads it this way at Romans 4:25 (*delivered up because of our transgressions, raised because of our justification*) and 1 Corinthians 15:3-4 (*Christ died for our sins according to the Scriptures... and was raised on the third day according to the Scriptures*). Isaiah 53 is one of the *Scriptures* Paul has in mind."
